================================================================================
PART 3: TECHNICAL ATTRIBUTIONS
================================================================================

This project implements established cryptographic and bioinformatics techniques.
The algorithms themselves are not original inventions but rather implementations
of well-known standards and methods. Proper attribution is provided below:

### SHA-256 Implementation
- Standard: FIPS 180-4 (Secure Hash Standard)
- Original authors: National Security Agency (NSA) and National Institute of
  Standards and Technology (NIST), United States Government
- Status: Public domain (U.S. government work)
- Reference: https://csrc.nist.gov/publications/detail/fips/180/4/final
- Note: This project uses a pure JavaScript implementation of the SHA-256
  algorithm as defined in the FIPS 180-4 standard.

### XOR Cipher with SHA-256-derived Keystream
- Technique: Symmetric stream cipher using XOR operation
- Origin: Fundamental cryptographic operation, no specific author
- Status: Public domain (mathematical concept)
- Note: The XOR cipher is one of the oldest and simplest encryption methods,
  dating back to early cryptography. This project uses it in combination with
  a SHA-256-derived keystream for enhanced security.

### Key Derivation (SHA-256 + Counter Mode)
- Technique: Counter mode (CTR) key derivation
- Origin: Standard cryptographic technique used in AES-CTR and similar ciphers
- Status: Public domain (established cryptographic method)
- Reference: NIST SP 800-38A (Recommendation for Block Cipher Modes of Operation)
- Note: This project implements a simplified counter mode using SHA-256 to
  generate a pseudo-random keystream from a user-provided key.

### DNA Encoding (2-bit to Nucleotide Mapping)
- Technique: Binary to nucleotide base mapping (00→A, 01→T, 10→G, 11→C)
- Origin: Established technique in bioinformatics and DNA data storage research
- Status: Scientific knowledge (no single author)
- Key references in the field:
  * Church, G.M., Gao, Y., & Kosuri, S. (2012). Next-generation digital
    information storage in DNA. Science, 337(6102), 1628.
  * Goldman, N., et al. (2013). Towards practical, high-capacity, low-maintenance
    information storage in synthesized DNA. Nature, 494(7435), 77-80.
  * Yazdi, S.M.H.T., et al. (2015). A rewritable, random-access DNA-based
    storage system. Scientific Reports, 5, 14138.
- Note: The 2-bit to nucleotide mapping is a standard encoding scheme widely
  used in DNA data storage research. This project applies it to text encryption.

### Conceptual Framework
The combination of DNA encoding with cryptographic techniques for text
encryption represents an original compilation and implementation by the author
(Paris Lavin). While the individual components are established techniques,
their specific integration into this application is original work.

